item.description:
&lt;p&gt;Showcasing the brand new LP &lt;em&gt;Musically Bad&lt;/em&gt;: &lt;strong&gt;Tippa Lee meets the Naram Rhythm Section&lt;/strong&gt;, out soon on &lt;strong&gt;Red Robin Records&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Plus the killer new compilation of &lt;strong&gt;Libyan music&lt;/strong&gt; from cassette culture, spanning the 80s to early 2000s courtesy of &lt;strong&gt;Habibi Funk Records. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You&#x27;ll also hear the new &lt;strong&gt;Afrobeats from Burna Boy&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;amp; up to the times dancehall by &lt;strong&gt;Chronic Law &amp;amp; Rytical. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:14px&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:arial,helvetica,sans-serif&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:rgb(8, 8, 9)&quot;&gt;Lila Iké spreads love All Over the World on her new single with Protoje, Buju Banton is back to his oldschool best the new dancehall banger Full A Craft.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:14px&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:arial,helvetica,sans-serif&quot;&gt;Lila Iké has officially announced her debut studio album, &lt;strong&gt;Treasure Self Love&lt;/strong&gt;, which is scheduled to drop on &lt;strong&gt;August 22, 2025&lt;/strong&gt;, via Wurl Iké Records and Protoje’s In.Digg.Nation Collective, under exclusive license to Ineffable Records.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:14px&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family:arial,helvetica,sans-serif&quot;&gt;Buju Banton returns in vintage form with &lt;em&gt;Full A Craft&lt;/em&gt;, a raw, heavyweight dancehall cut that harks back to his ’90s energy. It’s a reminder of why Buju remains a towering figure in Jamaican music.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This week on &lt;em&gt;Riddim Yard&lt;/em&gt;, we celebrate a moment in reggae history: &lt;strong&gt;Horace Andy’s successful solo audition at Studio One&lt;/strong&gt;, where his performance of &lt;strong&gt;Got to Be Sure&lt;/strong&gt; convinced Clement &#x27;Coxsone&#x27; Dodd to sign him.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Plus a few gems from Reggae Magic: a new collection from the great Jackie Mittoo on Soul Jazz Records. The album features a mixture of classic tunes and rarities from the period 1967-74, when Mittoo was at the height of his musical powers.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Alongside that: plenty of heavy roots rarities, including a standout track from &lt;strong&gt;Omar Bernard&lt;/strong&gt; — a little-known vocalist, reportedly just &lt;strong&gt;13 or 14 years old&lt;/strong&gt; when he recorded the haunting 1980 tune &lt;em&gt;Man A Kill Man.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This week on &lt;strong&gt;Riddim Yard&lt;/strong&gt;, we pay tribute to the trailblazing British female vocal trio &lt;strong&gt;Brown Sugar&lt;/strong&gt;, whose soulful harmonies helped define the &lt;em&gt;Lovers Rock&lt;/em&gt; subgenre of reggae. Formed in London in &lt;strong&gt;1976&lt;/strong&gt;, the trio—&lt;strong&gt;Pauline Catlin&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;Caron Wheeler&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;strong&gt;Carol Simms.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You’ll also hear the scorching new unreleased remix of &lt;strong&gt;Skillibeng&lt;/strong&gt;’s Big Bang featuring ‘Wurl Boss’ &lt;strong&gt;Vybz Kartel&lt;/strong&gt;, and up to the times dancehall from &lt;strong&gt;Cutty Ranks&lt;/strong&gt; on Garrison Entertainment&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Plus heavyweight roots steppers on the Robert ‘Flako’ Palmer’s Negus Roots label ft. &lt;strong&gt;Lacksley Castell and Pupa Tullo.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We open with a freshly remastered gem: Al Campbell’s 80s cover of &lt;em&gt;Declaration Of Rights&lt;/em&gt;, produced by George Pang and powered by Sly &amp;amp; Robbie. One of reggae’s most underrated voices, Al brings militant depth to this roots anthem – now back in high definition thanks to VP Records.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Also in the mix: &lt;em&gt;In the Beginning There Was Rhythm (Early Version)&lt;/em&gt; by The Slits – a 1979 session cut full of raw post-punk dub energy, stripped back and hypnotic before the final album polish.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;And we close out with dancehall heat from Ghana’s Shatta Wale and Vybz Kartel.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Adrian Sherwood drops his heavy new album &lt;em&gt;The Collapse Of Everything&lt;/em&gt; - a deep dive into dub mutations from one of the UK’s most fearless producers.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We rewind to the early 2000s with classic Vybz Kartel, when his raw energy was reshaping the dancehall landscape.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;And we spin Annette Brissett’s underrated 90s gem recorded with Sly &amp;amp; Robbie.&lt;/p&gt;
